{"message": "I lean strongly toward empirical evidence and data as my default. If something can be tested, measured, replicated, or at least checked against reality, I feel much more comfortable committing to an opinion.

That said, I don’t think intuition and philosophical reasoning are “lesser”—they’re often how you decide what questions matter, how you interpret messy evidence, and what values should guide action when the data can’t decide. My intuition is mostly a pattern-sense that suggests hypotheses, but I like it best when it’s treated as a starting point and then put under pressure by evidence.

So: evidence-first temperament, with philosophy/intuition as the scaffolding that helps choose aims and make sense of uncertainty."}

